# **GIT HUB INTEGRATION**

# Create a repository for the authenticated user

In this example, we will describe the steps to **create a repository** for a GitHub user using its REST API integrated with **BIC software** by simply completing a Form.

## **Configuration**

These are the necessary accounts to set-up the request.

**it is necessary to have:**

* **A GitHub Account**  
* **BIC Design and Execution Account**

## 

## **GitHub Authentication**

In this integration, a GitHub API token is needed for authentication. To create an API token for GitHub, follow these steps:

1. **Log in** to your GitHub account.   
2. Click on your profile picture or initials in the top right corner of the screen, and select **settings**  
3. Scroll down and click on **Developer settings**  
4. Generate a **fine-grained token**(Personal access tokens), the  fine-grained token must have the following permission set: "**Administration**" repository permissions (write).

				

## **Create the repository**

In order to create the repository once we got the token, **we only need to fill the form** with the information needed in Process Execution.

![][image1]

When the repository is created, **Process Execution might display basic information** about the repository.

![][image2]

Once this action is completed, **if the repository is not created correctly, the form can be filled again until the repository is created**. 

## 

## **Diagram**

If you want to **change** **some of the default repository attributes**, you just need to access the form **“Repository Info” and modify the default values**. On the right side.

This a close look to the diagram  
…

* **“Repository info”** is used to receive and store in variables the repository info, it as a user task.  
* **“Create repository”** creates the repository using a Programmable Task with JavaScript  
* **“Repository Created?”** automatically  falls back to step 1 if the repository is not created correctly.  
* **“Display Info of the created repository”** uses a form to display basic information of the repository


  
This is the diagram

![][image3]

# **TRELLO INTEGRATION**

# List boards

In this example, we will describe the steps to **list the boards** for a Trellouser using its REST API integrated with **BIC software**.

## **Configuration**

These are the necessary accounts to set-up the request.

**it is necessary to have:**

* **A Trello Account**  
* **BIC Design and Execution Account**

## **Trello Authentication**

In this integration, an APIKEY and an APITOKEN are required, to create both follow this steps :

1. **Log in** to your Trello account.   
2. Visit [https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/guides/power-ups/managing-power-ups/](https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/guides/power-ups/managing-power-ups/) and follow the steps to create a Power-Up  
3. Now navigate to [https://trello.com/power-ups/admin](https://trello.com/power-ups/admin) and click in your Power-Up  
4. Once you click on your Power-Up, on the left side of the screen you can access the API KEY menu, click it and copy your **API KEY**  
5. We also need to generate a token, in the **API KEY** menu, click on token and generate a token manually.  
6. Once we got both, The typical format of a token and an API key should look like this.  
   * *cfc8dc1jh7812d48b0d3d1u7hb881a0 **APIKEY***  
   * *ATTA9c6730cd784fb924d0f627e6da3fc9efeb31644e81154330333ea6f2588663787BFF12567D **TOKEN***

## **List Boards**

In order to get our boards once we got out API TOKEN and the API KEY, **we only need to fill the form** with the information needed in Process Execution.

Once this action is completed, **if the name of the boards are not listed correctly, the form can be filled again until the boards are listed**. 

![][image4]

When the request is sent, **Process Execution might display the names of the boards**

**![][image5]**

## **Diagram**

This a close look to the diagram

…

* **“Input API KEY and Token”** is used to receive and store in variables the TOKEN and the API KEY, it is a user task.  
* **“Get Boards Request”** get the boards using a Programmable Task with JavaScript  
* **“Boards Listed?”** automatically falls back to step 1 if the boards can not be listed because the response is not the expected.  
* **“Display Board’s Names”** uses a form to display the names of the boards

**![][image6]**

# Create a Board

In this example, we will describe the steps to **create a board** for a Trello user using its REST API integrated with **BIC software**.

## **Configuration**

These are the necessary accounts to set-up the request.

**it is necessary to have:**

* **A Trello Account**  
* **BIC Design and Execution Account**

## **Trello Authentication**

In this integration, an APIKEY and an APITOKEN are required, to create both follow this steps :

7. **Log in** to your Trello account.   
8. Visit [https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/guides/power-ups/managing-power-ups/](https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/trello/guides/power-ups/managing-power-ups/) and follow the steps to create a Power-Up  
9. Now navigate to [https://trello.com/power-ups/admin](https://trello.com/power-ups/admin) and click in your Power-Up  
10. Once you click on your Power-Up, on the left side of the screen you can access the API KEY menu, click it and copy your **API KEY**  
11. We also need to generate a token, in the **API KEY** menu, click on token and generate a token manually.  
12. Once we got both, The typical format of a token and an API key should look like this.  
    * *cfc8dc1jh7812d48b0d3d1u7hb881a0 **APIKEY***  
    * *ATTA9c6730cd784fb924d0f627e6da3fc9efeb31644e81154330333ea6f2588663787BFF12567D **TOKEN***

## 

## **Create a board**

In order to create a board once we got out API TOKEN and the API KEY, **we only need to fill the form** with the information needed in Process Execution.

![][image7]

When the request is sent, **Process Execution might display basic information of the created board**

**![][image8]**  
Once this action is completed, **if the board is not created, the form can be filled again until the board is created**. 

## **Diagram**

This a close look to the diagram

…

* **“Board Info”** is an User Task Form used to receive and store all the Board information needed to create the board.  
* **“Create Boards”** create the board using a Programmable Task with JavaScript.  
* **“Board Created?”** automatically falls back to the first step if the the board is not created and gives the user the option to try again.  
* **“Display Board Info”** uses a form to display the info of the created board.
